  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n- The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Federal Criminal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (money laundering)\n- 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (monetary transactions in criminal proceeds)\n\n3. State-Level Laws:\nMany states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n4. International Cooperation:\nThe U.S. also participates in international anti-money laundering efforts through organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force)\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize the process of disguising illegally obtained money\n- Impose reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Establish penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Provide frameworks for investigating and prosecuting money laundering activities\n\nThe laws are designed to prevent criminals from concealing the origins of illegally obtained money and integrating it into the legitimate financial system.",
